Introduction

I would like to re-analyze the RNAseq data published in this paper https://www.nature.com/articles/s41467-019-10197-x. Therefore, my task here is to determine whether a fold change of gene expression is different between two types of human stem cells derived from dental pulp (DPSC) and bone marrow (BMSC). In this report created with Rmarkdown, i would like to describe the workflow and tools that i used as well as the results obtained. I also make some interpretation and comments of genes differential expression analysis between BMSC compared to DPSC.

a. Retrieve the data : At first, I downloaded all six fastq files related to this project from Gene expression Omnibus link provided earlier using SRA tools and CLC genomics v10 download tool. the hg38 version of the human genome, including various annotations were also downloaded from Ensembl website.

b. Quality control : Quality control of raw reads was done using fastQC, a snapshot of the results can be seen here. Based on that QC report, I decided to trim the first 15 nt. I also filtered reads with PHRED score <20 and reads below 75 nucleotides of length.

c. Reads mapping : Mapping of the quality trimmed reads to the hg38 version of human genome was done.Readss alignement for each sample was done using CLC genomics v10 read mapper. Its mapping algorithm is very similar, but faster than Bowtie short reads aligner. Alignement workflow can be seen here. The NGS reads mapping to human reference genome was successfully done because more than 90% of reads were correctly mapped; as shown in the following mapping report. A file containing total read counts (generated by CLC genomics workbench V10) was imported into R for downstream statistical analyses. All imput data used below were provided for reproducibility.

d. Statistical analyses : Negative binomial model was fitted to each normalized count for each sample and Wald test was performed to estimate the fold change of total RNA read counts in BM-MSCs compared to DP-MSCs. The statistical methods used here have been implemented in DESeq R package. The Benjamini & Hochberg p-value adjustment methodology was used to correct for multiple testing. I also made several plots to inspect the data before and after differential expression analyses. DPSC samples were used as reference in our comparisons.

2-Quality check of sequencing data

There might be multiple technical bias involved in RNAseq experiment such as batch effects, library size, genes length etc. Ideally, it is preferable to minimize bias from the beginning of the experiment because, there is a famous adage in statistics garbage in barbage out. Our goal here is to control or even minimize those bias during our analyses. Let us make some quality control exploratory plots.

# load the DESeq2 package
dds = DESeqDataSetFromMatrix(countData = count_data,
                             colData = col_data,
                             design = ~ condition) # below I will do PCA based on the cell condition
dds$condition <- relevel(dds$condition, ref="DPSC")# setting DPSC as comparison reference

h-Principal component analysis (PCA)

#Principal component analysis is a statistical procedure that uses an orthogonal transformation to convert a set of observations of possibly correlated variables into a set of values of linearly uncorrelated variables called principal components. This transformation is defined in such a way that the first principal component has the largest possible variance, and each succeeding component in turn has the highest variance possible under the constraint that it is orthogonal to the preceding components. The resulting vectors are an uncorrelated orthogonal basis set (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Principal_component_analysis). 

plotPCA(rld, intgroup=c("condition"))

PCA is often used to visualize distance and relatedness between samples. Plotting 1st and 2nd principal components (here representing 89% of total variance) shows separates DPSC samples from BMSC samples. I could have investigated other possible batch effects, but the authors of the paper did not provide other experimental data such as RNA integrity number, sequencing lane number etc. lane effect < flow cell effect < library preparation effect < biological effect (page 8[http://www.nathalievialaneix.eu/doc/pdf/tutorial-rnaseq.pdf]) Note that the total variance explained by PC1&PC2 of this PCA is higher than the total variance explained by PC1&PC2 in the paper of Shen WC et al, nat comm, 2019.

I-MA plot before differential expression

#An MA plot is an application of a Bland-Altman plot for visual representation of genomic data. The plot visualizes the differences between measurements taken in two samples, by transforming the data onto M and A scales, then plotting these values. In many microarray/RNAseq gene expression experiments, an underlying assumption is that most of the genes would not see any change in their expression; therefore, the majority of the points on the y-axis (M) would be located at 0, since Log(1) is 0. If this is not the case, then a normalization method such as LOESS should be applied to the data before statistical analysis (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MA_plot).
x = pseudoCount[, 1] # extract counrs of the 1st column
y = pseudoCount[, 4] # extract counts of the 4th column
M = x - y # M-values (differences between samples)
A = (x + y)/2 # Average values 
df = data.frame(A, M)
ggplot(df, aes(x = A, y = M)) + geom_point(size = 1.5, alpha = 1/5) +
  geom_hline(aes(yintercept = 0), color = "blue3") + 
  xlab("Average gene count") +
  ylab("Count difference") +
  ggtitle("M-A plot for SRR6189571 vs. SRR6189574")

Thiis is a plot of the difference in expression against the mean expression level. There is still a high variance for lowly expressed genes, because we used the log2 transformation of counts to make this plot. as shown earlier, regularised logarithmic transformation would be better.

3-Differential expression analysis usig DEseq

The null hypothesis here is that the logarithmic fold change between BMSC and DPSC for a genes expression is exactly zero, i.e., that the genes expression level (at all) is not affected by the phenotype of mesenchymal stem cell.

dds = DESeq(dds)# DESeq runs several functions including mormalization, fitting of negative binomial model, Wald test and correction p-value.
# DEseq will fits the relation between the mean and variance.
# plotDispEsts(dds, main="Dispersion plot") 
# The black points are the dispersion estimates for each gene as obtained by considering the information from each gene separately.Therefore, the red trend line is fitted, which shows the dispersions dependence on the mean, and then shrink each gene's estimate towards the red line to obtain the final estimates (blue points) that are then used in the hypothesis test(Bernd Klaus[ et al,2016).

a-Building the results table

res <- results(dds, alpha=0.05) # to see differentially expressed genes with adjusted p value above 0.05 as done in the paper

b1-MA plot after differential expression

#There might be a lot of noise associated with log2 fold changes from low count genes. DESeq2 can produce shrunken log2 fold changes that are more precise.
# It looks at the largest fold changes that are not due to low counts and uses these to inform a prior distribution. So the large fold changes from genes with lots of statistical information are not shrunk, while the imprecise fold changes are shrunk .

resultsNames(dds)
## [1] "Intercept"              "condition_BMSC_vs_DPSC"
res = lfcShrink(dds, coef="condition_BMSC_vs_DPSC", type = "apeglm")
plotMA(res, ylim=c(-10,10), alpha=0.05)

# Red points have adjusted pvalue < 0.05.

This plot demonstrates that almost all genes with a large average normalized count contain sufficient information to yield a significant call. Now let us plot the results as fold-change (log2) versus unadjusted p-value (-Log10) in a volcano plot plot.

b2-Volcano plot

library(EnhancedVolcano)
EnhancedVolcano(res, lab = rownames(res), x = 'log2FoldChange', y = 'pvalue',

res <- res[order(res$padj), ]

names(resdata)[1] <- "Gene_id"

Conclusion

Our filtered list of differentially expressed genes contain 3603 differentially expressed genes (1981 downregulated and 1622 upregulated) in BMSC compared to DPMS. Majority of genes (80%) uniformly expressed in both types of stem cells. Authors of this paper, found 3064 differentially expressed (DE) genes (p-value with FDR correction < 0.05), including 1359 upregulated and 1705 downregulated genes in BMSCs, compared to DPMSCs. Several possible reasons might explain the higher number of DE genes obtained in this exercise : (1)I used the Ensembl version hg38 of the human genome for mapping, which is well annotated (compared to refseq). (2)DEseq is very sensitive to lowly expressed genes when compared to other tools such as EDgeR, limma+voom etc, (and probably Partek flow) (3)other reasons???

Although the method that i used and the method used in the paper of Shen WC et al. were somehow different, there is a high number of overalpping differentially expressed genes is 2171 (out of 3064).

The functional analysis and gene ontology of these differentially expressed(DE) genes can be further done using other bioinformatic tools such as GSEA, REVIGO, GORILLA, DAVID, IPA etc..

As mentionned in the instructions of this assignement, those DE genes are only related to each type of cells (we do not know wether these genes induce stem cels differenciation).
